<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="stakeholder-register">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>project-manager</domain>
    <summary>Identify stakeholders, analyze power and interest, classify into Power-Interest quadrants, define engagement strategy, and store as version-controlled YAML to track attitude changes over time.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>stakeholder-identification</tag>
      <tag>power-interest-grid</tag>
      <tag>register</tag>
      <tag>yaml-schema</tag>
      <tag>engagement-strategy</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>pm</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Stakeholder Register</title>

    <summary>Identify every person or group who affects or is affected by the project, analyze their influence (power) and interest, classify into Power-Interest quadrants, and define an engagement strategy per quadrant. Store as YAML in source control; generate Markdown view from it. The rule: verify attitude through direct conversation, not inference — written communication is systematically polite and will produce false "Supportive" ratings.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Projects stall when high-power stakeholders feel bypassed, or when teams waste communication cycles on low-influence parties while ignoring blockers. The Power-Interest grid gives a systematic, evidence-based way to allocate engagement effort. Treat the register as live data — after each stage gate, archive the old version so you can track how perceptions changed.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Project initiation: before charter sign-off, identify who funds, approves, uses, blocks</item>
        <item>Bid/proposal phase: capture buyer, economic buyer, technical buyer, end users</item>
        <item>Cross-functional rollout (pricing change, ToS update, new platform) with regulatory and legal stakeholders</item>
        <item>Agency engagements: register both client-side and agency-side stakeholders</item>
        <item>After a reorg or M&amp;A where the old register is stale</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Fully internal personal-tool project with only you and your manager</item>
        <item>Pure agile team building for itself with one PO and no external dependencies</item>
        <item>Pre-discovery exploration where stakeholders are not yet defined — do problem framing first</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="identification">
      <p>Identify every person or group who affects or is affected by the project. Include indirect stakeholders often missed in initial brainstorms.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Project team members and leads</item>
        <item>Management, executives, sponsors</item>
        <item>Customers and end users (often listed as a group, not individuals)</item>
        <item>Suppliers and vendors</item>
        <item>Regulatory bodies, security council, data privacy, accessibility</item>
        <item>"Who can stop this project for 2+ weeks?" — the most important identification question</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Identify groups as groups (e.g., "Security Council", "Beta Customers") when a single person is not authoritative.</statement>
        <rationale>Splitting a group into individuals loses the fact that the authority is collective. An agent that lists "Alice, Bob, Carol from Security" implies any one of them can unblock — they cannot.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="power-interest-grid">
      <p>The Power-Interest grid allocates engagement effort based on stakeholder influence and interest in the project outcome.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Manage Closely (High Power, High Interest) — active engagement, involve in decisions; weekly or more frequent contact</item>
        <item>Keep Satisfied (High Power, Low Interest) — regular updates, no surprises; bi-weekly contact</item>
        <item>Keep Informed (Low Power, High Interest) — regular communication, gather feedback; weekly status</item>
        <item>Monitor (Low Power, Low Interest) — minimal effort, watch for quadrant changes; monthly summary</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use evidence (org chart, budget authority, RACI) for Power rating — not gut feel.</statement>
        <rationale>Two PMs produce different power ratings for the same stakeholder. Anchoring to org-chart position and budget authority makes ratings defensible and consistent across project phases.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Verify attitude through direct conversation, not from written communication inference.</statement>
        <rationale>Written communication (email, Slack) is systematically polite. Agents reading written transcripts will over-classify stakeholders as "Supportive". Only direct conversation reveals resistance.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="register-data-schema">
      <p>Store stakeholder data as version-controlled YAML so changes produce auditable diffs and history.</p>
      <example type="good" title="YAML schema with two sample stakeholders">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
- id: S-01
  name: Olena Kravchenko
  role: VP Engineering
  dept: Engineering
  interests:
    - delivery cadence
    - tech-debt reduction
  influence: H        # H | M | L
  impact: H
  attitude: supportive  # supportive | neutral | resistant | unknown
  quadrant: manage-closely  # manage-closely | keep-satisfied | keep-informed | monitor
  comms:
    cadence: weekly
    channel: 1:1 + Slack DM
  notes: Sponsor for Q2 platform initiative.
  last_touch: 2026-04-22

- id: S-02
  name: Security Council
  role: Group
  dept: Security
  interests: [compliance, audit-trail]
  influence: H
  impact: M
  attitude: resistant
  quadrant: keep-satisfied
  comms:
    cadence: bi-weekly
    channel: review meeting
  last_touch: 2026-04-15]]></code>
        <note>Quadrant is auto-computed from influence × interest but stored explicitly so changes are visible in diffs.</note>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Store attitude as "unknown" when no evidence exists in inputs — never invent an attitude.</statement>
        <rationale>An agent that infers "supportive" from polite email tone produces a false register. Unknown flags the PM to gather direct evidence before trusting the classification.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="attitude-classification">
      <p>Attitude classification is the most error-prone step. Require explicit evidence and direct conversation.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require attitude evidence as a quoted string from source material; reject any attitude assignment without a quote.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents systematically over-classify as "Supportive" because meeting transcripts and emails are written in professional, polite language. Requiring a quoted source prevents pattern-matching on tone.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Agents extract names from email signatures and infer seniority from job title — many blockers are mid-level gatekeepers (procurement, security review)</item>
        <item>Group stakeholders get split into individuals if you ask the LLM to "list people" — preserve the group when authority is collective</item>
        <item>Mid-level "influencer" stakeholders are systematically under-rated; explicitly prompt for "who has a veto even if not in the org chart?"</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="privacy-and-pii-handling">
      <p>Stakeholder registers frequently contain sensitive information and regulated PII. Separate sensitive data from the canonical register.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep PII (email, phone, salary) in a separate access-controlled file; the in-repo register holds only ID and role.</statement>
        <rationale>A stakeholder register committed to a shared repo exposes sensitive contact and compensation data. Separation allows broad repo access while restricting PII to those who need it.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Do not publish the full register to stakeholders themselves — attitude fields are internal; redact before sharing</item>
        <item>Apply the same access control tier as the project charter (executive-only for High-Power stakeholders)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="register-maintenance-and-refresh">
      <p>A static register decays rapidly. Systematic refresh and archiving track how stakeholder engagement changes across project phases.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Refresh the register after each stage gate; archive the previous version to track attitude changes over time.</statement>
        <rationale>A stakeholder who was Low-Low at kickoff can become High-High at launch (e.g., security team). The archived history shows when and why the quadrant shifted — valuable for post-mortems.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Track last_touch field; automated weekly diff vs comms log flags Manage-Closely stakeholders with zero recent contact</item>
        <item>Use the register as input to RACI, Communications Plan, and Risk Register</item>
        <item>Capture interests in concrete language: not "wants project to succeed" but "wants &lt;50ms p95 latency at launch"</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Agents can assist with initial identification and tracking, but human judgment is essential for attitude classification and strategy selection.</p>
      <p>A subagent can mine the project charter, kickoff transcripts, org chart, and Slack/email metadata to produce a draft register, then prompt the human for missing fields (interests, attitude). Treat the register as data: store as YAML/CSV in repo, generate the Markdown view from it. Human-in-loop required for attitude classification — agents systematically over-rate "Supportive" because written communication is polite. Refresh schedule: weekly at minimum during execution; daily during launch week.</p>
      <list>
        <item>PM agent — initial draft from charter + org data</item>
        <item>Business-analyst agent — cross-checks register against requirement sources (every elicited requirement traces to a stakeholder)</item>
        <item>Improver agent — periodic audit: which stakeholders haven't been engaged in N weeks?</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-integrations">
      <p>Command-line tools and SaaS integrations support register automation and analysis.</p>
      <list>
        <item>yq — query/update YAML stakeholder data in pipelines</item>
        <item>jq — process JSON exports from Salesforce/HubSpot</item>
        <item>gh api — pull GitHub org members for tech stakeholder identification</item>
        <item>pandoc — render YAML to DOCX register for sponsor review</item>
        <item>csvkit — pivot register CSV by quadrant for analysis</item>
        <item>Salesforce / HubSpot CRM — source of truth for external stakeholders; REST API available</item>
        <item>Notion / Airtable — native database with relations and automations to track engagement</item>
        <item>Smartsheet — common in enterprise PMOs with REST API for integration</item>
        <item>Confluence + Jira — pages for register plus Jira components for engagement tasks</item>
        <item>1Password — store sensitive contact credentials separately from register via `op` CLI</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Proven practices prevent common failures in stakeholder identification and engagement tracking.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Identify groups, not individuals only — "Security Council", "Beta Customers" — when a single person is not authoritative</item>
        <item>Capture interests in concrete language: not "wants project to succeed" but "wants &lt;50ms p95 latency at launch"</item>
        <item>Verify attitude in conversation, not from inference — written tone is a poor signal</item>
        <item>Refresh after each stage gate; archive the previous version (audit trail of how perception changed)</item>
        <item>Use the register as input to RACI, Communications Plan, and Risk Register (resistant high-influence stakeholder = risk)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <p>Be aware of the boundaries and failure modes of the Power-Interest model.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Captures snapshot, not dynamics — attitudes shift; pair with Stakeholder Engagement (advanced)</item>
        <item>Overlooks indirect/silent stakeholders (legal, security, data privacy, accessibility, end users)</item>
        <item>Power-Interest grid hides time dynamics: someone Low-Low at kickoff can become High-High at launch</item>
        <item>Privacy/PII concern when emails, phone numbers, salaries are stored — apply access control (e.g. NDA, role-gated repo paths)</item>
        <item>"Influence" rating is subjective; two PMs produce different grids. Use evidence (org chart, RACI, budget authority) not gut feel</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-profile.md" purpose="Individual stakeholder profile with interests, concerns, and engagement history"/>
    </templates>

